The poem, which was placed on the pedestal afterwards, and to which you refer, is not part of it".
Miller's factually correct, but as he pointed out, this isn't about history.
Above all, the striking words of Emma Lazarus resonate today - an invitation not just to immigrants, but to the poorest of the poor: 'Come to me, you who are downtrodden, you who are poor, you who can hardly breathe freely, you miserable worms in the midst of crowded cities.'
And it is in modern times that we can see these "miserable worms" more than ever on our screens.
Miller wasn't trying to criticize poetry - he wanted to make it clear that these people were not welcome in the United States.
