Emma Lazarus, as well as her friends who sought to place a plaque with a poem on the base of the statue after her death, knew well enough that she was playing a high political game.
The statue was intended to express the union of French and American republican governments by representing the classical theme of the female embodiment of liberty.
Emma Lazarus altered this meaning: in her poem, the female figure is not abstract, but has her own voice.
She also has a very different name, Mother of Exiles.
Merging poetry with the idea of womanhood is a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And in the same way that Emma Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, right-wingers have long sought to reverse that meaning.
