Before the arrival of the Christians, the local people worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes", says Bardina, pointing to her colorful, hand-knitted turban, dark shirt, and bright skirt.
"Before, we only carried leaves".
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line and some of the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But at the same time, Indonesia is the land of gold.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, Arizona, is only 60 miles from Paniai - a rocky province about the size of New Jersey that is home to about 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports an estimated $78 billion worth of logging.
For the Papuans, however, these riches are a source of suffering and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian military.
A 2005 New York Times investigation found that Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 per officer.
Papuans calling for self-rule are threatening this golden goose and are being severely repressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands more raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in the Papuan tribal region during the 1970's amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes atrocities that took place last year as extrajudicial executions, torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular, according to another report - and a brutal crackdown on peaceful protesters.
"It is difficult to count the number of casualties because the incidents happen every week", said Andreas Harsono, Indonesian researcher for Human Rights Watch.
To make matters worse, Papua's resources are attracting settlers to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million people, 83 percent claim to be Christian, but the demographics are changing with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixture of vegetables and peanut sauce.
The locals are struggling to survive.
"Immigrants started selling chickens and vegetables at traditional markets at lower prices than the local Papuans", explains Abeth You, 24, who was born in Paniai and moved to the provincial capital, Jayapura, to work.
"The original inhabitants of Papua - the mama-mama (women) - thus lost their jobs".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to address inequality and rights violations during his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured passage to the presidential palace in Jakarta from 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But little has changed in Papua, and the local people feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because in 2014, we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would hear our call for justice", You said.
The reality is that just two months after Jakowi's inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a major shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were singing Christmas carols around a campfire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorbikes emerged from the night.
Two of the surprised children told them that they should turn on the lights.
One soldier was moved by the rebuke and the tone of voice, and he later returned with four other soldiers, said local priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the soldiers, intoxicated, chased a group of children and beat them with the butts of their weapons, victims and witnesses said.
One of the soldiers then fired on a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby election commission building, and things escalated the next day.
Some 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on a soccer field outside the local police station and army headquarters to demand justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita - a circle dance imitating the song of birds - of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua New Guinea.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the buildings.
As tensions mounted, soldiers were ordered over the radio: "If the crowd attempts to resist at least three times, you have permission to shoot", said an official document, the contents of which have never been made public in the local media, according to TIME magazine.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of Enarotali Kego Koto, recognized the danger and urged residents to return to their homes.
But no one was to heed his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist", he told TIME from the porch of his brightly painted wooden home.
Kayama still doesn't know who the shooter was, but according to him, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting", he added.
One local resident, Alfius Youw, was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to the body to make sure it was really him", Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME in a somber voice.
"I saw he was dead... and I kissed him".
Papua's police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were merely "securing" the station, which was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death", Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many others were injured.
The news of the murders was all over the Jakarta media the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi made an impassioned speech in Jayapura expressing his sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never happen again", he said.
According to the Office of the SRSG on Children and Armed Conflict, he was responsible for recruitment and use of children in Ituri from 2002 to 2003.
Almost immediately, however, excuses began to be made.
"Most acts of violence happened a long time ago.
Some of these occurred in the 1990's and some in the early 2000's.
I mean, we are determined to punish these violent acts, but it will not be an easy task", he said.
However, in a June 5 interview with TIME magazine in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he had no plans to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said that "all cases will be brought to trial".
Wiranto, who has been accused by the UN of "crimes against humanity" over more than a thousand deaths during East Timor's 1999 independent elections, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had been settled so far, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the Paniai shooting victims greeted his claim with disbelief.
"I've been questioned four times in the last three years, but so far I haven't received anything", said Yohanes.
"I'm tired of it".
Years later, he says, he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid", as he says.
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the army or shot".
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many Paniai residents who are afraid to talk about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the military after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army came looking for me", he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in nearby Deiyai.
The clash, which left one person dead and 17 others injured, was between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to help transport an unconscious man to the hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company building.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at them and fired warning shots in response.
However, locals claim that the Mobile Brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd, killing one person.
"There was panic, we were afraid of retaliation", Domingu Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded arrive, told TIME.
"I didn't leave the house for two days".
Deiya's parliament demanded that the police involved be punished and that the mobile brigade be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the side of the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the isolation of the indigenous Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal people who live in the central highlands.
Many have joined the Papuan Liberation Movement (PLM), a rebel army that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and kidnapping Indonesian police.
Some of the OPM leaders are from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of attacks in recent years, the military has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of Paniai residents, all under the pretext of "ensuring national sovereignty".
Some of them no one will ever see again.
Paniai is known among Papuans as a "tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty adds fuel to the fire.
The little rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
And bread is equally unattainable.
The inhabitants grow their own food - mainly sweet potatoes, fruit, and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields, each cultivating four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is consumed by the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since the opening of Nabire airport and the influx of new immigrants into the country, economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants has increased.
Already scarce jobs tend to be filled by better educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital and education needed to start a business.
"Young people are moving out of the villages because of lack of jobs and money", said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Due to its isolation, Papua province is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists - Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp - were expelled from Papua for "lack of cooperation with the authorities", despite being granted rare permission to film.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy director of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokowi campaigned on promises to end restrictions on journalists and achieve transparency and development.
"Foreign journalists working in the restive easternmost areas of Papua and West Papua face a high risk of visa denial and blacklisting", he said in a statement.
The lack of reporting by foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesia over Papua is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and the Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the accusations, telling reporters in Jakarta: "Indonesia is still a democracy and the media is free, so it is difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations".
Locals are calling for foreign governments to get involved.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals chanted "we want freedom", according to a source who also attended the meeting but asked not to be named.
Indonesia is scheduled to hold another election in 2019, but Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
