He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai - besides living in constant fear of a marauding army - are mired in poverty, poor education and healthcare.
Gobai claims that Paniai residents, like other Papuans, see their vote as a "debt" to Jokowi.
"They don't want money, they want justice", he added.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniagua shooting continue with a final symbolic act of defiance: burying the bodies of the victims in a plot across from the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done, at least they won't let those responsible forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed", said Yacobus, his head bowed.
"What can we do?"
The French Navy intercepted a huge shipment of cocaine bound for Australia.
The French Navy intercepted a yacht in the Pacific carrying 1.46 tons of cocaine worth approximately $256 million.
The shipment was bound for Australia.
During the operation, the four-member crew of the ship, believed to be of Lithuanian and Latvian nationality, were arrested.
The yacht, named Afalina, had set sail from South America and, after being seized by police, was towed to the port of Nouméa, the capital of the French overseas territory of New Caledonia in the Pacific.
The Australian Security Intelligence Organisation said it would work with its international partners to determine exactly where the drugs were coming from and where they were going, and to uncover the "Lithuanian syndicate".
"We are grateful to the French authorities for the measures they have taken to stop large quantities of drugs going to Australia", said Col Blanch, its executive director.
The drugs were destroyed this week in Noumea.
High street prices make Australia an attractive target for drug traffickers.
The country also faces the problem of a growing number of drug addicts.
The current raid is not the first in recent times.
