Seniors don't feel thirsty, they need to be reminded to drink.
According to Pavla Mádlová, a doctor at the Geriatric Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague, the solution could be infusions of saline solution, which are injected under the skin with a thin needle.
But they're only used in healthcare settings.
As a person ages, the amount of water in his body decreases.
"In addition, they lose their thirst sensation, so they generally drink less and become dehydrated very quickly", said Mádlová.
They should definitely drink two liters.
"But getting that much fluid into an old person is a big problem", she added.
In nursing homes, she says, there is often no doctor in sight.
In hospitals, they usually treat dehydration with IV fluids.
"I think it should be phased in there as well so they can get the subcutaneous infusion", she said.
According to her, up to two pint bottles of saline can be given to the elderly each day.
Lack of fluids can cause drowsiness, headache and reduced performance.
Dehydration will manifest as a complete loss of self-sufficiency.
"One day the old man says he can't get out of bed, he talks incoherently", she added.
If neglected, it can even result in a stroke.
The blood thickens and clogs a blood vessel in the brain, which can lead to kidney failure.
Lying patients should not be covered with a blanket, preferably a cotton sheet.
Disposable diapers can also be a problem.
"It's more nursing", she said, "but the ideal would be to expose the patient occasionally and let the skin breathe".
For the second time, The Torch burned in Dubai.
In Dubai, fire engulfed one of the world's tallest residential skyscrapers on Friday, forcing firefighters to evacuate all occupants of the 1,100-foot-high [337 m], 79-story building.
This is the second fire in two years at the high-rise, aptly named The Torch.
All occupants of the building have been evacuated and no injuries have been reported.
"We were asleep when the alarm went off and we heard screaming.
It took us 10 minutes to run down from the 50th floor", one resident, George, told Reuters.
Dubai Civil Defence said firefighters brought the blaze under control at about 04:00 (01:00 GMT) and continued to cool the building.
Government officials added that they were providing alternative accommodation for affected residents.
The incident could reignite debate about the safety of materials used to clad tall buildings around the world.
The results of the investigation launched by the management of the Torch skyscraper after the fire in 2015 showed that the most damaged were the cladding and external panels used for decoration or insulation.
British police say that the insulation and cladding system at London's Grenfell Tower may have contributed to the rapid spread of the fire that killed nearly 80 people in June.
Surveys show that more than 1 in 5 travelers to the United States takes banned items on an airplane
A survey of passengers revealed that more than 20 percent had knowingly or unknowingly carried prohibited items through U.S. Transportation Security Administration checkpoints, and at least 6 percent had boarded a plane with a knife or other sharp object.
Less than 1 percent of the travelers said that they discovered too late that they were carrying firearms, ammunition, or explosives.
The results of a survey conducted by Stratos Jet Charters Inc. - with more than 1,000 respondents - revealed that younger passengers are more likely to break the rules.
Of the respondents who admitted to knowingly attempting to travel with an item prohibited by the TSA, 19.7 percent were passengers with several thousand hours of flight time, compared to less than 15 percent of Generation X members.
The most common items to escape TSA scrutiny are food and alcohol.
More than 3 percent of the respondents knowingly carried a sharp object through security, while 2.2 percent of the women and 3.7 percent of the men polled also admitted to having deliberately brought illicit drugs on board.
The company said that it conducted a survey of travelers worldwide to find out how many accidentally brought illegal items through airport security and how many did so intentionally.
Not surprisingly, most people who have carried illegal items - whether knowingly or unknowingly - travel by air frequently.
As the company pointed out, TSA guidelines are somewhat complicated and confusing.
People often do not know what liquids and how much they can take on an airplane.
Not surprisingly, the TSA seized the largest amount of illicit liquids.
For a while, people thought the TSA would treat books the same way they treat contraband.
Carriage of liquids is permitted on domestic flights but not on international flights.
EPA head Scott Pruitt on the delay of the Obama administration's planned emissions reduction guidelines
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by 15 states, its head Scott Pruitt reversed his earlier decision to delay the implementation of the former Obama administration's plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt has introduced changes to his plan that make it more responsive than previous administrations to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he made no mention of a legal challenge to his former position before a federal appeals court.
This concerns the deadline of 1 October for countries to comply with the 2015 regulation to reduce ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay the deal for one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid "interfering with local decisions or threatening economic growth".
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma's attorney general before being appointed by President Donald Trump to head the EPA, has long served as a staunch opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since taking office in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly pushed back or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's abrupt reversal is the biggest legal setback yet for Pruitt's regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA administrator overstepped his authority in trying to delay the implementation of the Obama administration's plan to require oil and gas companies to reduce methane emissions.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt proposed his version of the ozone standards and reinforced the EPA's commitment to working with states through a comprehensive process and meeting the new standards within a set time frame.
"Under the previous administration, the EPA often missed deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settlements and rescheduling", said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We don't believe in regulating through litigation and we take meeting deadlines seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes with it".
However, the EPA statement notes that Pruitt may at some point use "the power of delay and all other legally available authorities" to ensure that regulations "are based on sound policy and the best available information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive overhaul of ozone regulations.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure still hasn't passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states suing the EPA this week, said the group would not cave in to legal pressure.
"The EPA's reversal - following our lawsuit - is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution", added Schneiderman.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone is produced when common pollutants released by automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants, and other sources react with sunlight in the atmosphere.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in susceptible people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists are applauding Pruitt's sudden change of heart.
"It's alarming how much pressure it takes to change minds and protect the air we breathe", said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to fight the Trump administration's ideological crusade to help polluters and special interests".
He threw acid on a man, yet the courts say he's not dangerous.
You never know what's gonna happen.
One minute, you're at home with your family, laughing, and the next, your whole life changes.
And the worst part is, there's nothing you can do about it.
A similar fate befell Andreas Christoforos of Great Britain, whose face was attacked with acid by an unknown assailant who was eventually acquitted.
The news was reported by Reuters.
In December 2014, there was a knock on the Christopheros' door.
Andreas got up to answer the door.
He assumed that a courier was at the door to deliver Christmas presents for the family that day.
Instead, a cruel surprise awaited him.
A man he'd never seen before poured acid on it without warning and said, "This is for you, buddy".
The pain was indescribable.
The clothes fell off me like nothing, and all I felt was excruciating pain in my skin", said Andreas.
His family rushed him to the hospital, but there they received devastating news - the doctors had given him up for dead!
For weeks after the incident, doctors worried constantly that their patient would succumb to an infection that threatened to seep into his wounds.
His injuries were very serious.
Ninety percent involved the face, which doctors tried to rebuild using skin from other parts of the patient's body.
A major complication for Christopheros was the loss of his eyelids.
It's probably the most excruciating thing I've ever experienced.
"You can't hide from the unexpected light, you can't close your eyes", he described his ordeal.
Today, Christopheros has undergone 12 operations, and he is far from finished.
According to plastic surgeons, the injuries suffered by victims of acid attacks can require hundreds of surgeries and years of treatment.
Even after intensive, long-term treatment, victims have scar tissue for the rest of their lives.
"Sometimes people never recover and struggle with deformity and disfigurement for the rest of their lives", said Professor Peter Dziewulski, spokesman for the British Association of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons.
The attacker made a mistake.
As for the attack, Christopheros is sure that the unknown man must have mistaken him for someone else.
The perpetrator believed he was taking revenge on the man who sexually abused his loved one.
Police investigated the case thoroughly and eventually tracked down the attacker.
The man was originally sentenced to a minimum of eight years in prison.
Later, however, the verdict was reversed, much to the astonishment of Christopheros' family.
"The three judges ultimately concluded that the sentence should be quashed because the man is not considered a threat to the public", said Christopheros.
In the last few years, the number of attacks by corrosive substances has increased considerably.
The Ministry of the Interior has commented that it plans to establish new guidelines for prosecutors on the classification of corrosive substances.
They should be classified as dangerous weapons.
Victims of such attacks, however, are not about to give up.
They are demanding that the UK government enforce tougher and longer prison sentences for people who attack their neighbours with acid or other corrosive substances.
They also call for stricter controls on the sale of dangerous substances, which are often commonly available in shops as different cleaning products.
