Thursday was the hottest day of the year.
In the Hodonín region, they measured 38.3 degrees Celsius.
Tuesday's temperature record of 98.6 degrees Fahrenheit only lasted two days at its peak.
With a temperature of 102 degrees Fahrenheit [38.3°C], recorded at Watchtower Farms, it was surpassed on Thursday, making it the hottest day so far this year.
This has been confirmed by the Czech Hydrometeorological Institute.
But unlike Tuesday, not many temperature records were broken on Thursday.
On Tuesday, records were broken or equalled at 35 of the 145 weather stations measuring over 30 years.
On Thursday, only nine long-term monitoring stations recorded record temperatures.
For example, in Watchtower, Thursday's temperature was the same as the previous record set in 2013.
In Lednice near Břeclavsk, Thursday's 37.4 degrees exceeded the original maximum by four tenths of a degree, and in Pohořelice near Brno, today's 37.1 degrees exceeded the record by three tenths.
Both records, like the Watchtower, were from 2013.
It was ten degrees cooler in the west.
High temperatures on Thursday occurred mainly in the south and east of Moravia.
After Strážnice, the hottest places were Dyjakovice in Znojmo region and Brod nad Dyjí in Břeclav region, where the mercury reached 37.8 degrees Celsius, but the record was not broken.
On the other hand, in western and northwestern Bohemia, for example, Thursday's high temperatures were only about 72 degrees Fahrenheit [22°C], according to the Czech Meteorological Institute website.
"Temperatures did not begin to rise there until later this afternoon", the weather service reported.
According to the Czech Meteorological Office, the current heat wave in the Czech Republic will gradually subside and more significant rains could come on Sunday.
In most parts of Moravia, however, high temperatures will remain on Friday and in the southeast of Moravia on Saturday.
China is missing tourists.
Beijing is losing billions because of the visa policy.
For decades, China has sought to exert its influence without the use of force.
It spends $10 billion a year to support language schools and build universities abroad, pushes its entertainment industry into foreign markets, and tries to attract Western tourists.
That's what's wrong with Beijing.
State media there are talking about a plan to make tourism a driver of economic transformation and modernization.
However, arrivals grew by only 3.8 percent last year, and about 80 percent of the tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan.
For all its global aspirations, China is not exactly welcoming to foreigners, according to Christopher Balding, a professor of economics at Peking University, in an article for Bloomberg.
The most telling example is China's visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free access to China, the citizens of the others must obtain a visa in advance.
As a result, crowds at Chinese consulates in the United States are comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
The visa costs $140, but if you do not want to wait in line for hours, you may have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study in the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the visa requirement reduces the number of visitors to a country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's GDP and less than one percent of its population.
China often exacerbates the problem when it uses tourism to advance its political goals, such as in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted shipments to South Korea this spring in a dispute over South Korea's missile defense system, the South Koreans retaliated by shunning China.
In May, the number of visits dropped 42 percent year on year, while Japan saw an 85 percent increase.
All this has an impact on macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent U.S. Federal Reserve report, as much as $190 billion may have left China as a result of Chinese travel abroad, while China earns about $35 billion annually from foreign exchange sales to inbound tourists.
According to official balance-of-payments figures, China ran a $217-billion deficit in tourism last year, equivalent to 44 percent of its entire merchandise trade surplus.
Thus, the low number of tourists deals a severe blow to a country anxious to prevent capital flight.
