Massacre at Moore's Ford Bridge: activists remember racist lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past a crowd of onlookers in Monroe, Georgia, and sped toward the Moore's Ford Bridge.
Before the car with four black passengers and a white driver reached the bridge, however, a group of white men with guns blocked its way.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - took a long drag on his cigarette and stared into the windshield.
Inside, the passengers were trembling with fear.
"We want that nigger Roger!" shouted the man.
"Bring him to me!"
The silence is broken by the screams of a young black man being pulled from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is merely a reenactment of the events of July 22.
But when one of the men throws the noose around "Roger's" neck, the audience gasps with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists has regularly returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct the fateful night in 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Ku Klux Klan.
No one has ever been prosecuted for the murders.
"It's strange that in all these years not a single person has been arrested - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know who they are", said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the reenactment.
"It is a stain on our history and a burden on our souls".
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reenactment is a dramatic call to action, an annual reminder to the Monroe community that justice has not been served.
"We demand prosecution and closure, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all", Brooks said.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin".
A medical examiner covers one of the bodies of a lynching victim at Moore's Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, as many as 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were involved in the lynching.
However, no one has ever been prosecuted.
Although the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates claim that the two motives for the lynching - politics and sex - were well-known to all the townspeople.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ruled that blacks in the state of Georgia could vote for the first time in elections scheduled for that summer.
And just in time for this summer's election, the FBI says a black farmer named Roger Malcom allegedly stabbed a white landowner named Barnett Hester during an altercation over his wife.
There was a rumor in town, according to Brooks, that Hester had intercourse with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and impregnated her.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, prominent white landowner Loy Harrison posted $600 bail for Malcolm.
Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey accompanied him to prison.
On their way back from the prison, just before entering Moore's Ford Bridge, they were blocked by a group of suspects.
"As it turned out, the murders were planned and organized by Harrison", the FBI concluded.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and local law enforcement who not only participated in the lynching but also disposed of the evidence and concealed the identities of the witnesses".
Brooks was more succinct about the whole thing.
"It was a massacre for the right to vote", he said.
"The murders sent a clear message to all local black residents: 'This is what happens when you register and vote.'"
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has organized an annual reenactment of the events at Moore's Ford Bridge.
Her performance is vivid, engaging and succinct, exposing a deep-seated racism that many would like to see eradicated from modern America.
It's not easy to watch this reconstruction, and it's even harder to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
"Nobody wants to talk about lynching because it forces us to confront the uncomfortable feelings that lurk in all of us", said Greene.
"But we can't have a relationship until you hear what I've been through".
The main rehearsals for this year's revival began in June, and on the very first day, approximately 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - swarmed into the room, where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is acting assistant director.
He's played the leader of the Ku Klux Klan for years, but he says the role is exhausting.
"I feel bad about it because it goes against who I am", Marbaugh said.
"I think it's very important to be reminded of this part of history regularly, because we never want to go back to that time".
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascone, who play Roger Malcolm, aka Barnett Hester, are rehearsing their roles.
The show opens with a scuffle - Malcolm arguing with Hester and accusing him of sleeping with his wife.
"Get the f--- off my property!"
You can't have Rascona.
There's a skirmish.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) bursts out laughing.
Greene has the biggest laugh of anyone.
"What happened?" asks the Rascona.
He is confused.
Was I too harsh?
"No", says Greene cheerfully.
"I just don't think white people said 'n--r' in that tone back then".
"Exactly", says one of the black actors.
"You have to put more emphasis on the R".
The energy in the room suddenly improves; hostility gives way to a feeling of closeness.
Everybody wants the show to be authentic, if only to make up for the four massacre victims.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time Rascona emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the N-word.
No one's laughing now.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The screams, the gunshots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings the mournful Billie Holiday song "Strange Fruit".
There's a sadness in the room with every word.
In the background, about a dozen onlookers wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple traveled all the way from Ithaca, New York, and many of the spectators are local.
Each of them endures the local humid climate for nearly eight hours, and Brooks leads them in procession to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until this point, the murders could be viewed from a distance, but now, standing on the very spot where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is eerie.
With the final words of the song, Greene challenges the crowd of onlookers to inspect the bodies.
Kids kneel by their victims' heads, watch the fake blood and motionless bodies and whisper in each other's ears.
"They're not dead", mutters the little boy.
A few minutes go by, and Greene thanks the audience.
The actors are cleaning the rope and wiping their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Ku Klux Klan.
Nick Rascon hugs his two fellow actors and cries in their arms; eventually, he is overcome with emotion.
"It's all right", one of the women whispers.
"We know you don't like the part.
But you did it for a reason".
Later that day, the audience sits down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple is talking excitedly about a performance with a black couple they met earlier in the day.
Denise Duplinski could barely find the words to express how she felt about tonight's performance.
"It's hard to listen to the ugly words and see the ugly deeds... done by people who look like you and do it because they look like you", she said of the reconstruction.
"It makes me realize that lynching is still a hot topic", she added, "it's just called police brutality".
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks is sitting in a courtroom, enjoying dinner while talking about civil rights.
In his own words, he's already started planning next year's show.
"The reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to live through - but it is also a moment for reflection", he said.
"If we don't learn from this, who knows... it could happen again.
A people who do not know and do not learn the history of their country are condemned to repeat it".
