Recent results of tests to determine the age limit for asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, which were subjected to a new method of assessing their age, show that over 80 percent of people interviewed were over 18, but not everyone trusts their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) started new tests earlier this year.
The measure was introduced after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has referred 6,880 cases for investigation and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests carried out between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were judged to be over 18, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency judged the interviewee to be "possibly over 18".
In a further 423 cases, it was decided that the respondent was "possibly under the age of 18".
Tests shall only be used if the age of the interviewee is in dispute.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency the results correspond to the previous month.
"Compared to last month, the statistics are stuck in a rut and the numbers are very similar", he told The Local.
The higher number of applicants whose age was estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases, "the respondent was 18 years of age or older".
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent said he would turn 18 this year.
Also criticized is the medical method of age determination, which involves X-rays of the wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints, which are then evaluated by dentists and radiologists.
One skeptic is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes measuring biological maturity to determine the age at which a person reaches puberty.
