"Summer of the Dead" and "Comrade Detective" play on the nostalgic theme
This iteration of the story is nostalgic for both the characters of the glorious 1980s; the sleazy 1990s (when geniuses David Wain and Michael Showalter hosted the MTV sketch comedy show "The State"); and, of course, modern times, specifically 2001, before stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, and Paul Rudd took off for bigger projects.
As a cultural artifact, it's both a light parody and an embodiment of our modern Facebook era of permanent memory.
From a franchise standpoint, it looks like someone's running out of steam.
"First Day of Camp" did surprisingly well - not least because of its absurd humor (such as the tale of a talking can of vegetables voiced by H. Jon Benjamin).
The authors deviated from the main joke point - middle-aged actors playing teenage horny children - and could not make fun of the previous events.
The sequel to "Ten Years Later", in which adults play adults, is less emotionally charged, and the satire is sporadic at times, including parodies of 1990s thrillers like "Hand in the Cradle".
At one point, the character finds an Apple Powerbook, roller skates, and "a bunch of other stuff from 1991" in a pile of junk.
Many of the major storylines are repeated.
Good-hearted Coop (Mr. Showalter), now a writer, still hasn't gotten over his love for Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a virgin.
Not to mention a crazy plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Mr. Showalter) instigated by George H. W. Bush (very well cast Michael Ian Black).
As always, the best part of a franchise is the many subplots.
Particularly entertaining is watching the eternally young, long-haired Rudd, aka Matt Dillon's character from The Young and the Restless, whose once-respectable Andy character is now an old fart.
The franchise could be kicked off by moments of random madness, like the returning series "Seven Up", until it reaches what I suspect will be its logical conclusion: "Wet Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later", where in the final scene, the entire gang heads to the premiere of "The Dead End".
Amazon's "Comrade Detective", meanwhile, appeals to a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War revivalism of "Ordinary Americans", the movie "Atomic Blonde", and even "GLOW", which pits Eastern and Western wrestling icons against each other.
Written by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Rhys Thomas, the comedy is intended to act as a television production: a drama about two Bucharest police officers in 1980s Romania who fight for truth and Marxist-Leninist atheism.
The main roles - the tenacious Gregor and the idealistic Joseph - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Cornelia Ulica, dubbed into English by Channing Tatum (executive producer of the series) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a wonderful idea.
Unfortunately, it's not much more than that.
Some jokes will make you laugh (such as cops watching chess on TV - a parody of American football).
Many well-known actors have lent their voices to the series, including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali, and Chloë Sevigny.
But "Comrade Detective" focuses too much on the clumsy propaganda drama - which includes a killer in a Reagan mask - and it looks that way.
Six long episodes is too long and not enough comedy.
In shorter footage, the propaganda satire in "Comrade Detective" might work, as in the scene where Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the U.S. Embassy, in whose lobby two fat men devour hamburgers stacked in a large pile.
The clear message to an imaginary communist audience is that Western culture can turn anything into food and orgies.
The imaginative Romanian creators weren't wrong: we do this to our own culture as well as theirs.
