Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among patients at risk.
Taking PrEP before sex means that the patient has enough of a particular medicine in their body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants to sign up for testing, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not already controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also register at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The programme will cost taxpayers £10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs after winning an international tender.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: 'This important intervention should complement and take full advantage of the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of trying to halt one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: 'We are witnessing a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if administered correctly and to patients at risk, offers the potential to transform the UK's HIV epidemic.
From September, the NHS will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and does not require a partner to be persuaded, improving the quality of many lives.
We welcome this declaration.'
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: 'Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of testing across the country; we must ensure it is available to every patient.
We now have an experimental drug called PrEP, and we're well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV".
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: 'The start of the PrEP trial is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of government delays and delays.
