High-rise living: mezzanine and clever design transform this tiny Earls Court flat into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, exchanged a large house in Knightsbridge for a flat in Earls Court in 2014.
Located on the first floor of the Queen Anne smart terrace - it is a prime example of modern design that makes the most of the available space.
"I had previously lived with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge", said Joanne.
"I was looking for something more reasonably priced.
I came across this flat in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I fell in love with him right away and said yes to him that very day".
Since then, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
A one-bedroom apartment with a complicated layout -- to get to the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen -- Joanne wanted to add storage and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceilings.
"I longed for high ceilings, large windows, and lots of light.
Those were my demands", she said.
To do this, she employed Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill-based design and development studio Duck & Shed and used a nearly four-metre ceiling to create a home that was not just a project but also a place to live.
The ceiling was not high enough for two gaps to overlap, so the challenge for the architects was to create a mezzanine level on which people could walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative mind.
"Steel construction is quite complicated", he explained.
"We had to rearrange both rooms so that we could walk upright.
It was not just a question of building a simple platform, but also of bending the steel structure to the right height above and below the ceiling".
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - and add drama at the same time.
The mezzanine overlooks the beautiful living room with old copper window frames in the Retrouvius design.
Mirrored furniture in gold, silver lines and a retro chandelier by Serge Mouille create a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor has mirrors on both sides, making it look longer.
The mirrored countertop in the kitchen looks like a window into another room.
At the entrance door there are storage compartments with mirrors to store cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of being much larger, is that it can be separated from the kitchen when not in use.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this design is the hinged door.
"We had to solve a technical problem", says Erfan of the reinforced veneer doors.
'The door is fitted with counterweights to enable it to be opened very easily.'
Through clever use of space and storage, Joanne gained an additional 54 square feet [16 sq m], a second bedroom, and a better layout.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is living space - or the appreciation of your property", Erfan said.
"Essentially, when a real estate agent enters an apartment, he calculates an estimate based on the square footage".
In this case, it has been possible to increase the living space while maintaining quality materials that give the space a luxurious look.
"The material is very important because you touch it and you create an emotional bond with the home", Erfan added.
"You don't fall in love with the wiring in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but they will not win your heart".
As it turns out, good design and increased living space can transform an ordinary apartment into something extraordinary.
And like Joanne, you may eventually decide to stay.
