Today, however, in the wake of recent events, they meet mainly for their own safety.
They learn the importance of changing their habits.
Two respected journalists discuss what would be safer: taking your children with you to an office that was hit by a grenade in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three simple words on a blackboard: adversaries, neutrals, and allies.
They ask journalists to name every word - no evidence needed, just imagination and intuition.
There are many to choose from - drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, and journalists suspected of accepting money from governments or drug cartels - a catalog of criminals whose job is to cover up their criminal acts.
Violence continues and bodies are piling up across the country; journalists are on the rise: at least 25 have been killed since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists; 589 journalists are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and seven have been killed in all seven states this year.
Among them is the co-founder of the periodical Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The greatest mistake is to live in Mexico and work as a journalist", wrote Valdez in one of his many books on the violence associated with the drug trade.
His loss is palpable, though his presence is pervasive - a large photo of Valdez with the word "Justice" in the middle finger hangs on the building's facade; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - in their 30s, wearing a T-shirt with a photo of Valdez with a smile on his face, glasses on his nose and a Panama hat.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual traumas, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was created in 2010 to handle journalists' cases, so far it has prosecuted two suspects, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur each year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime, making it very rare for the killers of journalists to be brought to justice.
Riodoca journalists insist on reporting on the violence that is happening in Sinaloa; even though they are devastated by grief and the territory is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the killers and a vision of justice, the security meeting is pointless, says Ibarra.
"It is foolish to waste time on such meetings", he adds.
"Until we have more information, no one can be trusted".
