Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid their enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however terrifying.
Researchers have now revealed the first findings of an amazing rhino-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains - dubbed the 'Mona Lisa of dinosaurs' by experts - were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were so well preserved that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of its scaly skin and said that the dinosaur had a 'troubled past.'
According to an article in the journal Current Biology, it is "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best-preserved dinosaur genera in the world".
The fossil is a new species of Nodosauridae, a dinosaur that lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
Its perfect state of preservation shocked researchers, who described it as "remarkable indeed".
According to National Geographic, the platypus is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across what appeared to be a foreign object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Researchers spent the next six years working to unearth the animal from a massive 2,000-pound lump of earth.
With the work completed, the dinosaur is ready for unveiling.
'You only have to squint a little to believe it is asleep,' said Caleb Brown, curator and naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
'It will surely go down in the annals of history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.'
By studying its skin, researchers have determined that this herbivore - despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank - likely faced a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect itself from predators and used a camouflage system used by many animals today.
Experts say this allowed it to better blend in with its surroundings and avoid predators, and the camouflage system suggests it was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110-million-year-old Nodosauridae first appeared in newspapers in May, and it is currently on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who and his team spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly unearthing the fossil.
Thanks to the fossil's remarkable state of preservation, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shapes of scales and armor all over the body.
They discovered a method of camouflage commonly used by modern animals for defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its underside.
Although this camouflage effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because the Boreal's size far exceeds that of modern animals using the same technique.
So it's possible that the dinosaur was such a prolific predator that evolution favored camouflage over confrontation for survival.
Many modern animals with camouflage - such as deer, zebras and armadillos - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that Nosodurus had to literally fight for its survival.
'The sale of a huge and heavily armoured dinosaur illustrates the danger posed by Cretaceous predators,' said Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was likely a reddish-brown color.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for other clues about its life, including preserved stomach contents to track down its last meal.
They believe that after the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was carried to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
At that time, Alberta had a climate similar to that of present-day Florida, and rivers and oceans ran much farther inland than they do today.
'What's really remarkable about this nodosaur is that it's completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin and it's also preserved in three dimensions so we can see its original size,' Brown said.
'For these reasons, the animal looks virtually the same as it did in the Cretaceous.
You don't have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; just blink a little and it seems to be asleep.'
In the Cretaceous period, giant theropods walked the Earth, carnivorous dinosaurs that walked on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been a favorite prey of its equally fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, an 11-metre-long monster weighing over six tonnes.
Researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelt's body was washed out to sea after being mummified in mud.
The discovery was made by Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it's the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, complete from snout to hip.
The animal reached an average length of 5 meters and weighed up to 1,300 kg.
Two 18-inch spikes protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivore roamed what is now Canada until it ended up in a river that washed it out to sea.
His underwater tomb preserved the body in perfect condition.
The fossil remains of this species are also preserved to the extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic, 'finding one preserved in this way is like winning the lottery.
The longer I watch him, the more shocking the find seems.
