How did one activist learn the answer to the question, 'Whose Streets?'
On August 9th, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaking all over.
The day after arriving in New York City, a St. Louis native sat on the bed of her Airbnb room, scrolling through Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across a post by a high school student.
"An 18-year-old has just been shot dead by police and his body is still lying in the street", it said.
She was surprised that no one else had written this post for her, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
Twitter user @TheePharoah was constantly retweeting her wall posts.
The St. Louis rapper was tweeting about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot and killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying helpless in the street, unclaimed for four hours.
"This is crazy", Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put her phone away to return to it the night she saw tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the victim's father and was holding a sign that said, "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son!"
She was watching live news - one of the police officers was standing in front of a group of protesters with a leash in his hand and a barking dog at the other end.
In another video, she said, another police officer was holding a gun and pointing it at the crowd, shouting, "I will kill you all... animals".
"This is not normal", Ferrell said to herself.
"This is not the type of murder that we are used to and that we can call normal.
I got goose bumps all over my body.
"I was angry and I cried".
She immediately booked a return flight home the next day.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided to drive to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is chronicled in a new documentary, "Whose Streets?"
It's a story of survival and protest, love and defiance, strength and resilience told from the perspective of the people living in the community who took to the streets and demanded answers.
On the way to Ferguson, Ferrell struck up a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral sweater and the same floral headdress - about a topic they had discussed many times before - "the black experience".
"Remember when I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" she recalls the conversation.
"Right now, we're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old kid, and that's not right".
"There was no way I wasn't going to take her with me", Ferrell later said.
"Today's events are the culmination... of events that have occurred in the past.
She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow into it.
She needed to grow not only in activism and organizing, but she also needed to learn the difference between the different layers of black experience and what we need to do to liberate ourselves.
Even though I'm able to provide her with an environment where she doesn't experience racism firsthand, she's no different than any other black female child.
I feel that to shield her from this experience would only hurt her".
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop was South Florissant Road across from the police station, which became a base for activists awaiting word from Officer Darren Wilson about his possible involvement in the incident.
There, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who prepared meals for others.
Together, they packed food and helped distribute it to Protestants.
In Ferrell's eyes, a new kind of activism was slowly emerging.
"My activism was turned upside down after August 9", Ferrell said, adding that while in college at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and worked to bring health care and food to black communities.
"I had no organizational experience.
It was natural".
A few weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, who would later co-direct the documentary, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said that he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" the ongoing events.
But Ferrell wondered, "Are you working on a documentary or are you trying to find a story to use?"
And that kind of skepticism trickled down to the community through a lot of people, often white people, who wanted to capitalize on the pain and the determination.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often left out, and we wanted to change that".
Folayan has already teamed up with co-director Damon Davis, an acclaimed local artist who works with death row inmates.
His involvement in the project also interested Ferrell, along with six other locals who were followed by the "Whose Streets?" team in the years following Brown's murder.
"No one speaks for us in this document, but it is our testimony", Davis said.
"That was important to me - how these people would be represented - because that's how I would be represented".
While the documentary was not intended to focus on Ferrell's experience - in an effort to show that the movement "is not about a savior leader, but about bringing the community together", Folayan said - she turned out to be the most open to participating.
The documentary "Whose Streets?" thus describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, such as how he fell in love with his wife.
"I felt naked", said Ferrell with a smile on her face as she recalled the first moment she saw the final version of the documentary.
"But I realized that in order to do this work and humanize black people, I had to open up".
Additionally, Ferrell's story highlights the role of an eccentric black woman in the larger Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - which created the #BlackLivesMatter social media campaign in response to the 2012 killing of teenager Trayvon Martin - call themselves queer.
"Black queer women in leadership positions ultimately stand behind the preservation of the movement", Ferrell said, "because we're constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the brunt of these events".
Folayan agrees, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of queer black women".
However, he insists that "this is not just an affirmative action issue" and that Ferrell is not the subject of the documentary because of her views.
"She was the driving force and the source of energy", she said.
"it's no accident that she's on the front lines, "because living at these crossroads as a black queer woman is dangerous.
You can feel the rush of energy even in front of the screen".
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, the TV cameras have cleared their positions, but the difficult racial ties between the community and the police remain.
