A Becoming Resemblance: an artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
At the center of a room at the Friedman Gallery in New York City are several faces of different skin tones - white, black, and brown - suspended from the ceiling by wires, each seeming to pop out of the other's eye.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the unauthorized publication of classified cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is titled A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before he left office.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to depict what a person with that genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg has created a trenchant, if not intellectual, commentary on the malleability of DNA - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of those interpretations, as well as identities.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning and spoke of identifying as a woman from a young age, was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violating six espionage laws, computer fraud, and theft.
All photographs of her were withheld by prison officials, except for one poor-quality black-and-white photograph of a visibly distressed Manning in the driver's seat wearing the platinum blonde wig now associated with her.
In 2015, positive reactions to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 project Stranger Visions were still being heard.
For this project, Dewey-Hagborg used a variety of forensic items - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of what these people might look like.
And that's when she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison, and they wanted to do a portrait", Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, no visitors or photographs were allowed, so they approached Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in a DNA profile.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea was pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, days after the comic was published, President Obama called for Manning's release, a welcome change after several excruciating years in a military prison in Kansas.
It is indeed interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war on whistleblowers and transgender troops while trying to find new ways to use his tweets to incite hatred in areas he is supposed to support.
When asked about this peculiar timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything happens for a reason".
Under a statement by the artist on one of the gallery walls, Manning's huge signature (the "i" in her last name is crossed out with a heart) calls for an end to "self-inflicted factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G, and A written in pencil.
By arranging 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific vocabulary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope people take away from this that our genome doesn't matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and can be interpreted in different ways", said Dewey-Hagborg.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them".
The last copy of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the aforementioned graphic novel.
It shows Manning emerging King Kong style from the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win", it says.
"Never allow yourself to be silenced".
"It's a direct transcription of one of the letters", said the Philadelphia artist.
"I get goose bumps just thinking about it".
Manning has not yet visited the exhibit in person -- as was predicted in the comic -- but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic likenesses, lined up like a crowd of protesters.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibit, including a nearly five-foot-tall statue of Manning with her genetic haplogroups written in pencil.
"In the past they have been placed on walls, but this time I wanted them to have a crowd feel", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement taking on Chelsea's form and liberating her".
