Startups that will keep your company from becoming another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but she couldn't find an appropriate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even misleading.
And although she promised anonymity for the inquiry, some employees have expressed their distrust of the process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity", said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New HR start-ups are constantly emerging to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By building and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee engagement, startups allow companies to conduct quick polls, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer complete employee anonymity and a complaint hotline, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact the CEO directly.
"There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that after three years of using Glint, she had become more aware of what her employees were thinking and feeling.
In addition to quick surveys and polls of specific teams, Glint offers a company heat map and a cursory view of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as a view of managers with low ratings - allowing the user to work on a fix.
Companies are waking up to the need to be mindful of workplace culture - in case they become the next Uber - which has been rocked by scandals after a former employee posted a blog post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let's Talk Payments, a website dedicated to technological and financial advancements, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small spike in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandals.
Convercent's nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
He also recently took Uber under his wing.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable "flash" surveys, collect real-time intelligence, and display heat maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
"The court of public opinion has empowered regulators", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of startup Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreating its employees or engaging in unethical behavior - and if regulators don't step in - it can face costly consequences from customer boycotts, employee burnout, or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to increase employee awareness of company policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he had to look up the company's phone number or e-mail address, file a formal complaint, and hope for a favorable resolution.
It was often a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday's general counsel, who said there was previously no reliable way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, it is able to quickly detect and resolve problems that previously never reached managers sitting in offices miles away from actually dealing with complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"It's getting closer to a holistic, holistic view of the employee experience", said Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday's group overseeing risk management.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from employee lawsuits".
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed following the collapse of Enron over employee ethics abuses, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until "social media lit up the whole thing" that companies began to realize they couldn't just keep their skeletons in the closet in the online world.
"Before people used technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith", Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service for which the companies pay recurring fees.
It's a business model and an opportunity endorsed by the venture capitalists who backed both startups.
Convercent raised a total of $10 million in its February campaign from firms including Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and ultimately took home $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and raised $60 million over the course of the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today's workers expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects aren't the main advantages.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued and that they are giving their time to a company that is pursuing a positive mission.
"If people are happy at work, feel that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they contribute to the success of the company", said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when companies do well, and companies do well when their employees are happy.
And when an analytics tool comes to market that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it's not surprising that there are a lot of investors who will support that effort.
According to experts on work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless if the company doesn't take the necessary steps.
The reality is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can happen.
And if change does not come quickly - or even at all - it can lead to employee frustration and disengagement.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations", said Russell Raath, director of consultancy Kotter International, who has seen many companies rely too much on data alone.
"Because when you don't follow through, employees start to wonder, 'Did they hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, can solve the problem in one day with Glint, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated with slow decision-making and poor communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and begin communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining vital insight into its workforce and hopes to achieve long-term high employment in an industry known for frequent layoffs.
"If you don't strive to create a transparent work environment, employees won't trust you", Vitrano added.
"And once you start losing employees, you start losing customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt".
