Making a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
Scotney Castle was recently featured in a Squeeze music video, and Margaret Thatcher took refuge there during the 1970's and 1980's.
But from his cozy perch on the River Bewl in Kent, England, Scotney has witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history that inspired curly-haired Yorkshire native Jamie Rhodes - known for his fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Looking at the handwriting of a man who has been dead for 300 years fascinates me", says Rhodes with a straight face.
"When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection".
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of the families who resided at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period, with each story illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by a thumbprint on a letter written in the 1970s by a double agent working for the Jacobites", he said.
"It's his thumbprint!
And the letters always smell like smoke because in those days you had to light a candle to read them.
When I smell that letter now, 300 years later, it's like I've gone back in time.
How I love the archives!"
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to stay at the castle for almost four months is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, going through the archives and studying the many treasures and curiosities, such as a hyena head on the wall and bottles that had been thrown into the moat for centuries.
He walked the grounds, examining the ruins of the old castle, talking to gamekeepers, gardeners, and occasionally the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
He was "drinking whiskey and writing" at night.
Scotney's private history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to the documents in 2006 after the death of the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived on the scene ten years later, the staff were just beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described as "the aristocrats of many centuries waving their hands and saying, 'Take it to the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British Empire, property maps: "You may think a land dispute is boring", Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch tree.
Knock it off, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
"I found a record of a castle revolt in 1380 in a book called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex", said Rhodes.
"The English rebellion actually began in this area, "and it occurred to me that rebellion was a good place to start.
Maybe there's a connection after all".
Other stories are firmly tied to the castle's history - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell who allegedly faked his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which wasn't discovered until years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male generation - back then men were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Generations of Darrells have dealt with this by marrying rich or old ladies - handsome gentlemen, I imagine, who liked to mess with the heiresses' heads".
With his stay at the castle over, Rhodes is looking for more adventure.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that has been swallowed up by nature.
But it's a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left", he said.
"I was like, 'Now I've got to get the hell back to real life.'"
