Sex robots are on the rise - we should be wary
Just when it seemed like 2017 couldn't get any weirder, a report about the technological development of sex robots appears on the Internet.
Yes, you did.
Sex robots are really popular right now.
The Foundation for Responsible Robotics (FRR) recently issued a statement on the development of sex robots within the next five to ten years.
According to former professor of robotics and artificial intelligence at Sheffield University and co-founder of the FRR, Noel Sharkey, the rise of sex robots needs to be taken seriously.
Customers can choose the color of the robot's eyes, the shape of its nipples, and the shape of its fingernails.
"People make fun of them, but sales are up, and we have to be prepared to see them more and more", Sharkey said when the report was released.
Modern sex toys are changing from inflatable men to robotic women with silicone skin that is pleasantly warm to the touch - not to mention artificial intelligence that mimics human behavior.
The user can "customize" the robot in his own image - from the color of his eyes and the shape of his nipples to the shape and color of his fingernails.
Of great concern, however, is the fact that many robots have a "personality" that would put even a Stepford wife to shame.
Modern sex dolls have evolved into robotic women with silicone skin.
The owner of the RealBotix robot can give his surrogate a variety of personality traits, including shyness.
And then there's True Companion's sex robot woman Roxxxy Gold, who comes with pre-programmed personalities, including "Frigid Farrah", who has a shy nature, and "Wild Wendy", who has an "adventurous" nature.
"Roxxy Gold's personality is set to match your personality as closely as possible", says the True Companion website.
So she likes what you like and you like what she likes.
It's even moody, like people.
She may be tired, talkative, or "in the mood".
The rise of sex robots is alarming for several reasons, not the least of which is the substitution for real human relationships.
The company True Companion on its website likens Roxxxy to a vibrator for men.
"If a woman can have a vibrator, why can't a man have a Roxxxy?" the site says.
But sex robots are not just a fetish or a sex toy.
Their emergence and near-perfect sophistication point to something darker and more deeply rooted in our culture - a shift away from an ideal or gender equality toward a desire for compelling sex with optional extras.
Of course, most men won't buy a robot wife, and while FRR talks about their growing popularity, sex robots still remain on the fringes of mainstream interest.
But this fringe interest can become a mirror set to the current modern age.
And most people aren't weird or violent unless the free market gives them an excuse.
It's no coincidence that these sophisticated sex robots are appearing at a time when women around the world are fighting for their rights and we have a president in the White House who is often very derogatory to women.
The most terrifying aspect of The Handmaid's Tale is not what we see - the hanged bodies and the gouged eyes - but rather the reality of these visions.
The Handmaid's Tale book proposal is a step in the right direction, but at the moment it seems to be a small step.
Sex robots are supposed to be as close to real women as possible (though with the proportions of a porn actress).
Their makers design them to be pleasant to the touch and to look like a real woman at first glance.
But when it comes to their "personality", a robot cannot replace a real woman.
They can't break up with their partner or just walk away.
They have no jobs, no history, nothing to encourage their independence or compromise their loyalty to their master.
In other words, they're pleasant slaves.
The language of the 21st century: service.
