Trump's big win?
On the other hand, Mitt Romney is the embodiment of common sense.
A sure sign of the Trump era is the political divisions that are dividing American voters and, on a micro scale, tearing families apart.
Over the Christmas and Thanksgiving period, American newspapers swarmed with advice on how to deal with relatives who voted for Trump.
Supposedly, we're just waiting for our nerves to give out.
Less attention has been paid to Trump's ability to bring families together.
I bring this up because I had a visit in New York this week from my cousin, a poet and left-wing groupie who lives in Chicago and who for a long time in our family paid the price for being a Republican simpleton.
She reminded me that coming together in the face of a common enemy can have a powerful effect.
Now, with Trump in the White House, suddenly the whole family - including all the Republican siblings with whom she's bickered about politics for years - is on the same page.
It's a good thing at the family dinner table, but it strikes me that in the larger context, it poses a significant risk.
Trump strengthens the left, but the negative effect of his presidency has the power to push us all to the right.
When we talk about "normalization" and Trump, we are referring to the frightening possibility that his antics may one day lose their appeal.
But there is an even more frightening long-term scenario in which Trump normalizes right-wing Republicans who, in defiance of his standards, suddenly become the embodiment of what can only be called rationality.
In these today, with a nostalgic heart, I remember Mitt Romney and his version of crazy behavior - dog on top of car, 14% income tax (at least we were aware of his tax returns) - both of which seem like very minor infractions compared to Trump.
With Trump gone, all the next Republican nominee has to do is be at least normal, which would be a huge improvement.
Taking advantage of my cousin's visit, we took the kids to Central Park for the largest carousel run by the New York City Department of Parks -- you can't do better with your three dollars, unless you need caffeine.
The horses are enormous, the central cylinder is covered with fiberglass - clowns and animals twirling and looking over their shoulders in horror - an utterly grim sight, and the jingling music is eerily reminiscent of public transportation.
Many clichés soon get old: the view from high buildings, the panorama stares rather than breathes, and the reality of the city doesn't match your imagination.
Thirty-five years later, I still can't get over the fact that Swiss Cottage isn't actually Swiss cheese - not counting the Ye Olde Swiss Cottage themed pub - but a London Underground station.
Nevertheless, the carousel in Central Park is a remarkably magical experience, so much so that two two-year-olds as well as two mature women can enjoy it.
If I could rate the merry-go-round, I'd give it maximum points, but fortunately, no one asks.
I had a similar experience this week at the grocery store when I was asked to rate my "experience" on a scale of one to five when paying with my credit card.
The coffee shop on the corner of my street is the same, except I can throw in a 15% tip for something I buy over the counter.
