Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may reduce the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare to your digestive system.
However, a new study suggests just the opposite: A diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 patients in the United Kingdom, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan in the protein helps produce immune cells that promote intestinal resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, who led the study, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure that harmful microbes in food are eliminated.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tip on the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
In the study, researchers found immune cells that promote tolerance in the stomachs of mice with a particular bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to build cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have found a link between one type of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a normal part of the gut microbiome, and the development of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had".
He also suggested that if the same turns out to be true in humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory gut environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, while studying a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of the same mice kept in isolation lacked them.
She deduced that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally inhabit the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the other group of mice lacked.
Mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked a gut microbiome -- so they didn't develop these kinds of immune cells -- were given L. reuteri bacteria, and they developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred a small amount of liquid - free of the bacteria - to immature immune cells that had been kept in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After the active ingredient was removed from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us carry L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the intestinal lining.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population.'
