A British inventor uses a microchip implanted in his hand to unlock his car and house with a wave of his hand
A British inventor has become the first person in the country to have a microchip implanted in his body, enabling him to unlock his home and office doors and even start his car with a wave of his hand.
Thirty-three-year-old Steven Northam had a tiny chip implanted between his thumb and forefinger and now offers the same service through his company, BioTeq, to companies and individuals who want to use technology to simplify their lives.
Dr Geoff Watson, an anaesthetist at the Royal Hampshire County Hospital in Winchester, is overseeing the implantation and follow-up procedures.
The technology works on the same principle as microchips implanted in dogs and cats, and the whole procedure takes 30 seconds.
Northam's company also offers a microchip-compatible door and car lock replacement service.
A married father of one has had the technology integrated into his home and his BMW Z4, which he starts with a wave of his hand.
White House props cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter onto the South Lawn to celebrate American manufacturing last month came at a cost of $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One when the president is on board, was the highlight of a July 17 White House tour of U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials toured a display of products from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire engine from Wisconsin, and a forklift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a Fragment Order, or FRAGO, requesting the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn as part of an "emergency" event, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event", the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's Deputy Chief of Naval Operations the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the parade, scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m., and would remain on site until the entire site was cleared, which was scheduled to occur between 6:00 and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail also stated that if there was a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent on the return flight due to working hours regulations.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening, along with a helicopter and a unit of security personnel.
The records - obtained by TIME magazine - did not indicate whether a second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We wondered if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was fine", the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you've been blocked", replied the deputy commander.
This "Made in America" show has been designated by the White House as an official event and therefore would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
During his appearance at the event, the president championed health care reform as it passed the Senate and spoke of his efforts to rein in government regulation.
The use of aircraft carriers such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation purposes is unusual.
Trump ordered the review in February after Air Force One hovered in the background of his first major campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida.
"The White House is delighted with the 'Made in America' exhibit, which showcases products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials", said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often practice landings in the Washington area and on the South Lawn, rehearsing eventual arrivals with the President of the United States at the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump was attending the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 practice landings near the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew's current training, a government official said.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew another 11 hours of 'non-presidential support missions'.
The White House said no additional props were paid for with taxpayer dollars.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in any way in the negotiations to display the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost associated with the parade is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly rate for Fiscal Year 2017 DoD expenditure reimbursements for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit logs show a 30-minute commute from the Marine Corps Air Facility at Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"Reporting the cost to taxpayers based on reimbursement estimates is highly misleading", Walters said.
'These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs.'
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD expenditure reimbursements do not include personnel costs, but include fuel, maintenance, and contract costs.
White House press secretary at the time, Sean Spicer, advocated the use of a helicopter for the parade.
"The idea of this week's show is to showcase American-made products", Spicer said.
"I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state, and that they employ hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, we're proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens have contributed to.
It is appropriate to recall that fact.'
It's unclear if Trump went to see the helicopter on his tour of the South Lawn, only that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know the Sikorsky very well", said the president, "I own three myself".
A young woman was trapped in a swamp at Moss Lake, and the police were on their way.
