Police dogs practiced helicopter flights on the bridge
Bomb-sniffing dogs and search dogs practiced helicopter flyovers at Bridge Lake today.
The police dog must not be timid and afraid of flying, said Petr Tomášek, head of the police cynologists of the Ústí Region.
Training a police dog takes about two years.
Both adult trained dogs and those still undergoing training were trained at Most.
In addition to the standard training of detecting sharp samples of explosives around the lake and searching for a missing stuntman, all 12 animals had to board a helicopter and fly over the lake.
The main purpose of the exercise is to test the dogs in the helicopter.
So as soon as the helicopter lands, the dog can go to work, so he doesn't have a problem with the helicopter ride.
"The helicopter lands, the dog goes and immediately searches", said Tomášek.
A dog that is restless or unable to start work immediately after a helicopter ride is eliminated from training.
"Usually, the handlers keep them in the garden, for example", Tomášek added.
The police have 76 dogs with different specialisations in the Ústí Region.
German Shepherds predominate, but Belgian Shepherds are also on the increase.
The handler's been taking care of him since he was a puppy.
"He is raising it himself, preparing it for the service the dog will perform for us", added Tomášek.
The animal shall be subjected to repeated veterinary examinations which may reveal any health handicaps.
If the dog is healthy and fearless, it takes its first tests at 20 months.
"Acute intervention takes about two and a half to three years", added Tomášek.
The length of police service depends on the health of the dog.
They usually serve eight to ten years.
