Get to know the plant with one click.
A new free app, Pl@ntNet, will help herbarium students and plant lovers alike.
If they're wondering what plant they just saw on their walk, this app will tell them.
All they have to do is take a picture of the plant, and the app automatically recognizes the species.
The new app, which is available for iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the Center for Ethical and Environmental Education CEEV in Bratislava's Mountain Park as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
Students from 50 Czech and Slovak schools took part in the project, photographing and adding plants from their surroundings to the app's database with their teachers.
A new French app can be downloaded for free from the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French developers was to get as many people as possible to contribute their photos to the app, thus increasing the number of plants the app can recognize.
"Children who already have a tablet or mobile phone in their hands can go into the forest", said project coordinator Ivana Poláčková.
On the basis of a sufficiently high-quality photo of a flower, leaf or fruit, the application can recognize its name within a few seconds, which it then assigns to the photograph in Czech and Slovak.
The French Secret Life of the City project allowed us to translate the app into Slovak and Czech.
Users are therefore welcome to contribute a photo of a plant that is not yet in the database after creating an account in the app.
"The French will evaluate whether it is useful and then add it to the database", Poláčková said.
GMB's concerns about the investment in the McVitie's plant in Glasgow
The unions are demanding assurances from the managers of McVitie's biscuit makers of a long-term commitment to the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish trade union GMB stated that the company was silent for the time being about a possible investment in the Tollcross plant.
More than 500 employees work at the factory, which produces Hobnob cookies and Rich Tea, among other products.
The owner of McVitie's, Pladis, said it had invested more than £5 million in the whole area over the previous few years.
It added that employees and trade union representatives would be 'among the first to be informed' in the event of changes in the factory's operation.
In a letter to the construction company, the Scottish GMB union expressed its concern that McVitie's 'will not deliver on its promises to fund and modernise production lines'.
GMB chief organiser Drew Duffy added: "The fact that we have not received a clear response from the developer about the needs of the community and the future investment plan at Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the employees are mostly drawn from the local community and the Glasgow area, where work in the factory is a critical pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
In terms of jobs, wages and benefits - and despite the prospect of Brexit, rising living costs and declining slow manufacturing - the east end of Glasgow desperately needs a thriving manufacturer like McVitie's".
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The manager of Tollcross Construction only received a letter from the GMB yesterday and the company will be issuing a statement as soon as possible as we appreciate the ongoing commitment to staff and union representatives.
A regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross took place two months ago and many issues were discussed openly at this meeting.
We discussed with our employees that, as with all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we evaluate our operations on a regular basis, which applies to all of our facilities, so that we can continue to compete successfully with others.
She added: 'We have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area in recent years, mainly in production lines and streamlining operations.
"We value the heritage of Tollcross and the surrounding area, "and any changes to the operations of the Tollcross plant "will be communicated to employees and union representatives immediately".
