The day before, the US imposed sanctions on Venezuelan President Maduro.
And the day before that, Trump tweeted that China was doing nothing about the North Korean threat and that it would not continue to do so.
Even that smacks of sanctions.
You can't lump those things together.
Maduro's Venezuela is indeed on the road to dictatorship, even totalitarianism.
China just isn't behaving the way the American president would like.
Russia is a chapter unto itself.
But if one wanted to summarize all this so that even the average voter, American, European or otherwise, could understand what the sanctions policy is all about and the system of rules that underpins it, it would be an almost impossible task.
In the sanctions against Russia, President Trump is just finishing what President Obama started, just giving it an executive stamp.
Then why all the fuss?
Last year, Europe feared that if Trump won the US election, he would embrace Putin and lift sanctions.
It's a terrible thought.
In practice, however, the opposite is true.
With Trump, sanctions are tightening, not loosening.
But Europe is even more frightened.
German Foreign Minister Zypries says Trump's sanctions violate international law.
Are you saying kosher means sanctions approved by the U.N. Security Council?
Then the EU sanctions against Russia are not kosher.
European Commission President Juncker has complained that Trump's sanctions threaten the EU's energy security.
Are you saying sanctions should only be used if they're weak enough not to endanger anyone?
The average voter is stumped.
For three years, he's heard that the fate of anti-Russian sanctions depends solely on the implementation of the Minsk ceasefire agreements in Ukraine.
Now we hear it's about the EU's energy security.
The voter's grasping and spreading.
Sanctions are coming down on Russia for putting too much where it doesn't belong.
China has been criticized for not assembling enough.
The Venezuelan president is being punished for building a dictatorship within his country's borders.
All these punishments or just considerations have their rationality.
But does anyone see a pattern, an order, a rule?
